JO  - The Journal of Finance
JA  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 469
EP  - 477
VL  - 44
IS  - 2
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.1989.tb05066.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT The ability of capital markets to distinguish firms of different value by the size of their initial equity offerings is attenuated when insiders can sell equity more than once. A model is developed in which there is price risk from holding equity between periods. When the uncertainty is small, there must be pooling in the first period. When uncertainty is large, the pooling equilibria dominate the separating equilibrium.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Effects of Beta, Bid-Ask Spread, Residual Risk, and Size on Stock Returns
AU  - AMIHUD, YAKOV
AU  - MENDELSON, HAIM
Y1  - 1989/06/01
PY  - 1989
DA  - 1989/06/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.1989.tb05067.x
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
JA  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 479
EP  - 486
VL  - 44
IS  - 2
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.1989.tb05067.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT Merton's [26] recent extension of the CAPM proposed that asset returns are an increasing function of their beta risk, residual risk, and size and a decreasing function of the public availability of information about them. Associating the latter with asset liquidity and following Amihud and Mendelson's [2] proposition that asset returns increase with their illiquidity (measured by the bid-ask spread), we jointly estimate the effects of these four factors on stock returns.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Price Effect of Option Introduction
AU  - CONRAD, JENNIFER
Y1  - 1989/06/01
PY  - 1989
DA  - 1989/06/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.1989.tb05068.x
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
JA  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 487
EP  - 498
VL  - 44
IS  - 2
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.1989.tb05068.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT This paper examines the price effect of option introduction from 1974 to 1980. The introduction of individual options causes a permanent price increase in the underlying security, beginning approximately three days before introduction. The price effect appears to be associated with introduction, and not announcement, throughout the sample period. Excess returns volatility declines with option introduction. Systematic risk is unchanged. There is a positive relation between the price increase and a measure of activity in the options market.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Adverse Selection in a Model of Real Estate Lending
AU  - CHARI, V. V.
AU  - JAGANNATHAN, RAVI
Y1  - 1989/06/01
PY  - 1989
DA  - 1989/06/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.1989.tb05069.x
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
JA  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 499
EP  - 508
VL  - 44
IS  - 2
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.1989.tb05069.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT We provide a rationale for the presence of points in mortgage loan contracts. Our analysis builds on two key features. First, insurance markets are unavailable for labor income. Second, the ?due-on-sale? clause allows banks to offer loan contracts which partially insure against fluctuations in labor income. If explicit prepayment penalties are prohibited by law, points serve effectively as prepayment penalties. We also examine environments where such penalties are not prohibited and show that points will be used if interest rates cannot depend on the size of the loan.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Institutional Ownership and Changes in the S&P 500
AU  - PRUITT, STEPHEN W.
AU  - WEI, K. C. JOHN
Y1  - 1989/06/01
PY  - 1989
DA  - 1989/06/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.1989.tb05070.x
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
JA  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 509
EP  - 514
VL  - 44
IS  - 2
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.1989.tb05070.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT Several recent articles have provided new evidence for the existence of price pressures by examining the price and volume effects associated with changes in the S&P 500. The present study extends this work by examining actual changes in institutional holdings following both additions to and deletions from the S&P 500. The results show that changes in institutional holdings in response to additions or deletions from the S&P 500 are positively correlated. In addition to providing further evidence for the existence of price pressure effects, the results also provide evidence of the very large institutional elasticities of demand for stock.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Expected Utility of the Doubling Strategy
AU  - OMBERG, EDWARD
Y1  - 1989/06/01
PY  - 1989
DA  - 1989/06/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.1989.tb05071.x
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
JA  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 515
EP  - 524
VL  - 44
IS  - 2
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.1989.tb05071.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT It has been noted that a certain continuous-time trading strategy, termed the ?doubling strategy?, generates a positive net return on borrowed funds, with probability one and within a finite period of time. Since the doubling strategy seems to represent a ?free lunch? or arbitrage opportunity, a variety of constraints to render it infeasible have been proposed. In this paper, we show that the doubling strategy generates infinite disutility for a large class of utility functions, and we can think of no utility function for a risk-averse agent which is a counterexample.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Comment on Forward Markets, Stock Markets, and the Theory of the Firm
AU  - MAKSIMOVIC, VOJISLAV
AU  - SICK, GORDON
AU  - ZECHNER, JOSEF
Y1  - 1989/06/01
PY  - 1989
DA  - 1989/06/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.1989.tb05072.x
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
JA  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 525
EP  - 528
VL  - 44
IS  - 2
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.1989.tb05072.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT In a recent article, MacMinn [5] argues that the presence of forward markets eliminates the incentives of the firm's manager to choose production levels that maximize firm value. In this comment, we show that his results do not depend on the presence of forward markets. The critical assumptions are that the manager is endowed with money rather than stock in the firm and that there is no competitive labor market for managers. In addition, his results require time-inconsistent behavior on the part of the firm's manager.
ER  - 

